posts.com:
I genuinely much prefer this over the Omega/Okada matches mainly due to the fact that it's driven by a clear face/heel dynamic. For my own preferences, that's where the magic of pro wrestling lies, because for those 40 minutes they managed to tune out the non-kayfabe aspects of the match in my head and had me legitimately marking out, in the sense that I was really rooting for babyface ospreay to get back into the match and win no matter what, I was hooked along with the crowd. To give you a better perspective, I'm someone who really liked the Tama/Karl match, and that's quite different from the usual formula that is reserved for omega and ospreay.
Kenny was as brutal as ever, and he didn't hamper his work with his usual over-the-top shenanigans, he kept the character work as close to the story as possible. He was wrestling to win, not to be "the best performer", and that was very refreshing for him. Even the V-Triggers were used as moderately as they should be, which increased their effectiveness as opposed to being mere filler. And my god did Ospreay have the selling of a lifetime ; that's how you become a hero. I believed, or wanted to believe, that he was going to kick out of the OWA, that he had to, after everything he's been through. I just wish they had an extra 5 minutes or so for the finish, because I felt like the crowd could have been even louder and had a gigantic pop for the finish.
The post-match promos were brilliant as well. I am now excited for the next chapters in this story.

posts.sub: I watched Omega vs Ospreay with my girlfriend…
posts.com:
She’s very new to the art of pro wrestling. She’s watched a handful of televised shows and been to one live Monday Night Raw event, earlier this year. Her favorite wrestler is Roman Reigns (surprise surprise).

Recently she has been showing more and more interest in watching wrestling with me. We even watched NXT on Tuesday night because it was the only wrestling on. I think most of her interest has to do with her supporting my passion (I’ve been watching for over 20 years), but I do think she is catching the wrestling bug, gradually.

Kenny Omega is my favorite active in ring competitor and I’m a simp for Will Ospreay, so I was so excited to blow her mind with what was sure to be a masterful display of pro wrestling. I dropped the $8 and started the show. She’s not a big enough fan yet to watch a 4 hour show straight through so I skipped to Kenny’s entrance and we settled in to our comfy slumber.

She quickly took a liking to Ospreay after his comeback offensive flurries. As a Kenny Omega mega fan, I reminded her that Kenny was playing the heel and Ospreay the face, so the match is constructed to get the fans behind the Aussie. Sometimes I talk too much.

We marveled together at the athleticism and fluidity of their movements. The table came out, and she thought the stomp was very well placed and safe and protected after they showed the replay of where Kenny’s impact came down. Just missing the mark, but undetectable at first glance.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>8505241
Then Ospreay got DDTed on the exposed top turnbuckle. We both gasped. The trainers and ring crew gathered around as Ospreay bladed. I did not give her insight into where the blood came from, and she fully believed it was legit. She’s in her fourth year of medical school so she has seen some serious trauma, but this effected her nonetheless. Tears started to stream down her face as Kenny punished the bloody Ospreay, but she couldn’t take her eyes off the screen.

Then Kenny leaned the punctured table up against the railing. Kenny grabbed Will’s head and smashed him face first into it. She covered her eyes right before the impact and cowered into me as I tried to comfort her with affection. Even my jaw dropped.

I knew there would be a comeback so I kept letting the match go on but it felt like an eternity of Omega brutalizing Ospreay. She watched with the covers pulled up over her nose and mouth. Ospreay’s eventual comeback was sweet, but it was too little too late. Even I was pulling for Will Ospreay at the end there.

This experience made me realize how numb I’ve become to the physicality of wrestling. If I had been watching alone, I would have just oohed and aahed the whole time, but experiencing it with her reminded me how serious this sport has the capability of being. She knows it’s scripted/ predetermined and she was still brought to tears in the moment. She called it “the craziest wrestling match I have ever seen.”

When it comes to psychology, that match had a PhD. And the underdog sympathy that was built around Ospreay will be so sweet once he eventually topples the One Winged Angel.

I was never great at writing in school and I’m not sure what point I’m trying to get across. This just felt like a story I had to share.
